inlineContent.text: The runtime calls this method after the gesture-recognizer state has been set to

—in other words, any of the terminal states for a gesture recognition attempt. Subclasses should reset any internal state in preparation for a new attempt at gesture recognition. After this method is called, the gesture recognizer receives no further updates for touches that have begun but haven’t ended.

abstract.text: Construct and manage a graphical, event-driven user interface for your iOS, iPadOS, or tvOS app.
The base class for concrete gesture recognizers.
The gesture recognizer has received touches resulting in the cancellation of a continuous gesture.
The gesture recognizer has received touches recognized as the end of a continuous gesture.
The gesture recognizer has received a multi-touch sequence that it can’t recognize as its gesture.
The gesture recognizer has received a multitouch sequence that it recognizes as its gesture.
Overridden to indicate that the specified gesture recognizer can prevent the receiver from recognizing a gesture.
Overridden to indicate that the receiver can prevent the specified gesture recognizer from recognizing its gesture.
Tells the gesture recognizer to ignore a specific touch of the given event.
Tells the gesture recognizer to ignore a specific press of the given event.

The current state of the gesture recognizer.
Sent to the gesture recognizer when one or more fingers touch down in the associated view.
Sent to the gesture recognizer when a system event (such as an incoming phone call) cancels a touch event.

abstract.text: For gestures that do not easily match a specific pattern, or when you want to use a gesture recognizer to gather touch input, create a continuous gesture recognizer.
If your gesture involves a specific pattern of events, consider implementing a discrete gesture recognizer for it.
A singleton actor whose executor is equivalent to the main dispatch queue.
